Queue module¶

class Queue.Queue(param: Optional[Any] = None)¶

Bases: object

FIFO (First-In Last-Out) Data Structure

Collection of elements with restriction on access. These are:
- Elements are added at the end and removed from the front
- There is no notion of specific position for elements other than element at the front.
- Repetitions are allowed
Implemented Queues with a circular array that gets expanded as needed

__hash__() → int¶

Generate a hash of this Queue using FNV1A hash

Makes a copy of this Queue and uses FNV1A hash with a little tweak (I use modulo 1E19 just so numbers don’t get TOO big)

Returns

This Queue’s hash code

Return type

int

Hint

Time complexity: O(n)

__init__(param: Optional[Any] = None) → NoReturn¶

Queue constructor

Parameters

any – integer, Queue or iterator that is used to prepare the Queue’s circular array.

Raises

TypeError – Occurs when param is not an integer, iterator nor other Bag

Example

>>> queue1 = Queue()
>>> queue1
[]
>>> queue2 = Queue([1,2,3])
>>> queue2
[1, 2, 3]
>>> queue3 = Queue(queue2)
>>> queue3
[1, 2, 3]
__repr__() → str¶

Converts current queue to string

Starts by making a copy and dequeueing all of it’s elements to a list. The elements of the list are then joined by commas

capacity() → int¶

Returns amount of elements circular array is capable of holding

As opposed to size/length, capacity establishes the maximum amount of elements container can hold

Returns

Capacity of queue

Return type

Example

>>> queue = Queue([3, 2, 1])
>>> queue.capacity()

Hint

Time complexity: O(1)

clear() → NoReturn¶

Removes all elements from queue

It practically resets the queue to it’s default state. However, it’s previous capacity persists

Example

>>> queue = Queue([3, 2, 1])
>>> queue
[3, 2, 1]
>>> queue.clear()
>>> queue
[]

Hint

Time complexity: O(n)

dequeue() → True¶

Removes element from the front of queue

Returns

True if operation was successful

Return type

bool

Example

>>> queue = Queue([3, 2, 1])
>>> queue
[3, 2, 1]
>>> queue.dequeue()
>>> queue
[2, 1]
>>> queue.dequeue()
>>> queue
[1]
>>> queue.dequeue()
>>> queue
[]

Hint

Time complexity: O(1)

enqueue(value: Any) → bool¶

Appends element at the end of queue

Besides appending to the end of the queue, it also checks if an expansion of the circular array is necessary

Parameters

any – The value of the element that will be appended

Returns

True if operation was successful

Return type

bool

Example

>>> queue = Queue()
>>> queue
[]
>>> queue.enqueue(1)
>>> queue
[1]
>>> queue.enqueue(6)
>>> queue
[1, 6]
>>> queue.enqueue(3)
>>> queue
[1, 6, 3]
>>> queue.enqueue(9)
>>> queue
[1, 6, 3, 9]

Hint

Average Time Complexity: O(1)
Worst-case Time Complexity: O(n)
expand() → NoReturn¶

Expand circular array capacity with which queue is implemented

Duplicates the capacity of the circular array by making a new Queue, enqueueing all this queue’s elements and copying all of the new queue’s parameters to this one

Hint

Time complexity: O(n)
